The '''bare-headed laughingthrush''' ('''''Melanocichla calva''''') is a [[species]] of bird in the Old World babbler [[Family (taxonomy)|family]] [[Timaliidae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to highland forests at elevations of {{Convert|750–1800|m|ft|abbr=on}} in the mountain ranges of north-central [[Borneo]], along with some outlying peaks. It is {{Convert|25–26|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, with both sexes similar in appearance. The head is brownish to greenish yellow and featherless. The area along the lower mandible has a bluish tinge. The rest of the body is dull blackish-brown tinged with grey. Juveniles have more feathers on the head, extending from the forehead to the {{Birdgloss|crown}}.

[[Species description|Described]] by the British [[ornithologist]] [[Richard Bowdler Sharpe]] in 1888, the bare-headed laughingthrush was then treated as a subspecies of the black laughingthrush from 1935 to 2006, when it was restored to full species status. It feeds on insects such as [[crickets]], [[cicada]]s, and [[ants]] in dense columns of vegetation formed by [[vine]]s growing around trees. Although it is classified as being of [[Least-concern species|least concern]] by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]], it is threatened by [[habitat destruction]] and [[Habitat fragmentation|fragmentation]] and its population is thought to be decreasing.

== Taxonomy and systematics ==
The bare-headed laughingthrush was [[Species description|described]] as ''Allocotops calvus'' by the British [[ornithologist]] [[Richard Bowdler Sharpe]] in 1888 on the basis of specimens collected from [[Mount Kinabalu]], [[Borneo]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Sharpe |first=Richard Bowdler |date=1883 |title=Further descriptions of new species of birds discovered by Mr. John Whitehead on the Mountain of Kina Balu, Northern Borneo |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/55018#page/417/mode/1up |url-status=live |journal=[[Ibis (journal)|Ibis]] |location=London |publisher=[[Academic Press]] |volume=30 |issue=4 |page=389 |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1888.tb08495.x |issn=0019-1019 |lccn=79010132 |oclc=1377260 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210420041108/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/55018#page/417/mode/1up |archive-date=2021-04-20 |access-date=2022-03-02 |via=[[Biodiversity Heritage Library]]}}</ref> It was subsequently considered a [[subspecies]] of the [[black laughingthrush]] (''Melanocichla lugubris'') by the English zoologist [[Frederick Nutter Chasen]] in 1935 and moved into ''[[Melanocichla]]'' as ''Melanocichla lugubris calvus''.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Chasen |first=Frederick N. |date=1935 |title=A handlist of Malaysian birds: a systematic list of the birds of the Malay Peninsula, Sumatra, Borneo and Java, including the adjacent small islands |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/209670#page/232/mode/1up |journal=[[Bulletin of the Raffles Museum]] |language=en |location=Singapore |publisher=Government Printing Office, Singapore |volume=11 |page=206 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.119907 |oclc=220730327 |via=[[Biodiversity Heritage Library]] |doi-access=free |access-date=2022-03-02 |archive-date=2020-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201029204731/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/209670#page/232/mode/1up |url-status=live }}</ref> In 1946, the French-American ornithologist [[Jean Delacour]] synonymised ''Melanocichla'' with ''[[Garrulax]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Delacour |first=Jean |date=1946 |title=Notes on the taxonomy of the birds of Malaysia |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/50979085#page/14/mode/1up |journal=Zoologica |language=en |location=New York |volume=31 |issue=1 |page=4 |doi=10.5962/p.184715 |s2cid=134523794 |issn=0044-507X |lccn=79009389 |oclc=1079318 |via=[[Biodiversity Heritage Library]] |access-date=2022-03-02 |archive-date=2020-11-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201126213003/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/50979085#page/14/mode/1up |url-status=live |doi-access=free }}</ref> In 2006, the British ornithologist Nigel Collar again raised the bare-headed laughingthrush to species status on the basis of differences in appearance.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Collar |first=Nigel J. |date=2006 |title=A partial revision of the Asian babblers (Timaliidae) |url=http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.600.8276&rep=rep1&type=pdf |journal=[[Forktail (journal)|Forktail]] |volume=22 |page=87 |citeseerx=10.1.1.600.8276 |access-date=2022-03-02 |archive-date=2022-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220302132828/http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.600.8276&rep=rep1&type=pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> The Spanish ornithologist Josep del Hoyo and colleagues split ''Garrulax'' into 11 different genera in 2007, placing the bare-headed and black laughingthrushes in a resurrected ''Melanocichla''.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Luo |first1=Xu |last2=Qu |first2=Yan Hua |last3=Han |first3=Lian Xian |last4=Li |first4=Shou Hsien |last5=Lei |first5=Fu Min |date=2009 |title=A phylogenetic analysis of laughingthrushes (Timaliidae: Garrulax ) and allies based on mitochondrial and nuclear DNA sequences |url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1463-6409.2008.00355.x |journal=[[Zoologica Scripta]] |language=en |volume=38 |issue=1 |pages=9–22 |doi=10.1111/j.1463-6409.2008.00355.x |s2cid=83800343 |access-date=2022-03-02|url-access=subscription }}</ref>

The name of the genus, ''Melanocichla'', is derived from the [[Ancient Greek]] ''melas'', meaning black, and ''kikhlē'', meaning [[Thrush (bird)|thrush]]. The [[Specific name (zoology)|specific name]] ''calva'' is from the [[Neo-Latin]] ''calvus'', meaning bald.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Jobling |first=James A. |title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names |publisher=[[Christopher Helm Publishers|Christopher Helm]] |year=2010 |isbn=978-1-4081-2501-4 |location=London |pages=86, 246 |language=en |oclc=1040808348}}</ref> Bare-headed laughingthrush is the official [[common name]] designated by the [[International Ornithologists' Union]].<ref name=":0">{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | editor3-last=Rasmussen | editor3-first=Pamela | editor3-link=Pamela Rasmussen | date=August 2022 | title=Babblers & fulvettas | work=IOC World Bird List Version 12.2 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/babblers/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | access-date=17 September 2022 }}</ref> Other common names for the species include bare-headed babbler<ref>{{Cite web |title=''Melanocichla calva'' (Bare-headed Laughingthrush) |url=https://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=6497AE0D61EB5364&sec=summary |access-date=2022-03-02 |website=[[Avibase]] |archive-date=2022-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220302132832/https://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=6497AE0D61EB5364&sec=summary |url-status=live }}</ref> and Bornean bald laughingthrush.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Sheldon |first1=Frederick H |last2=Brown |first2=Clare E. |last3=Rahman |first3=Mustafa Abdul |last4=Guan |first4=Khoon Tay |last5=Moyle |first5=Robert Glen |date=2013 |title=Ornithology of the Kelabit Highlands of Sarawak, Malaysia |url=https://lkcnhm.nus.edu.sg/wp-content/uploads/sites/10/app/uploads/2017/04/61rbz827-853.pdf |journal=[[The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology]] |volume=61 |issue=2 |page=846 |access-date=2022-03-02 |archive-date=2022-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220302132820/https://lkcnhm.nus.edu.sg/wp-content/uploads/sites/10/app/uploads/2017/04/61rbz827-853.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

The bare-headed laughingthrush is one of 57 species in the [[Old World babbler]] family Timaliidae,<ref name=":0" /> a diverse group of birds whose members are found in tropical forests in the [[Indian subcontinent]], [[Southeast Asia|Southeast]] and [[East Asia]], and [[Indonesia]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Winkler |first1=David W. |last2=Billerman |first2=Shawn M. |last3=Lovette |first3=Irby J. |date=2020-03-04 |editor-last=Billerman |editor-first=Shawn M. |editor2-last=Keeney |editor2-first=Brooke K. |editor3-last=Rodewald |editor3-first=Paul G. |editor4-last=Schulenberg |editor4-first=Thomas S. |title=Tree-Babblers, Scimitar-Babblers, and Allies (Timaliidae) |url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/timali1/1.0/introduction |language=en |publisher=[[Cornell Lab of Ornithology]] |doi=10.2173/bow.timali1.01 |access-date=2022-03-02 |journal=Birds of the World|s2cid=216471306 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> A 2019 [[phylogeny]] by Tianlong Cai and colleagues found the bare-headed laughingthrush to be most closely related to the black laughingthrush. These two species were further [[Sister group|sister]] (most closely related) to the genus ''[[Pomatorhinus]]''. The following cladogram shows the relationships within these two genera according to the 2019 phylogeny:{{Efn|The study treated the bare-headed and [[black laughingthrush]]es as a part of ''[[Garrulax]]''.<ref name="Caietal2019" />}}<ref name="Caietal2019">{{Cite journal |last1=Cai |first1=Tianlong |last2=Cibois |first2=Alice |last3=Alström |first3=Per |last4=Moyle |first4=Robert G. |last5=Kennedy |first5=Jonathan D. |last6=Shao |first6=Shimiao |last7=Zhang |first7=Ruiying |last8=Irestedt |first8=Martin |last9=Ericson |first9=Per G.P. |last10=Gelang |first10=Magnus |last11=Qu |first11=Yanhua |date=2019 |title=Near-complete phylogeny and taxonomic revision of the world's babblers (Aves: Passeriformes) |journal=[[Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution]] |language=en |volume=130 |pages=346–356 |doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2018.10.010 |pmid=30321696 |s2cid=53216358 |doi-access=free |bibcode=2019MolPE.130..346C }}</ref>

